'''Mushika Shrine''' (むしかじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Inuyama|Q503411|qid=Q503411|1=Inuyama, Aichi}}, {{ill|lt=Aichi Prefecture|Q80434|qid=Q80434|1=Aichi Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} ({{ill|lt=Owari Province|Q514506|qid=Q514506|1=Owari Province}}, {{ill|lt=Niwa District|Q1347719|qid=Q1347719|1=Niwa District}}).

=== Overview ===
Its founding period is unknown. It was also called Mushika Tenjin and Sanmyōjin Shrine.

Originally it stood in Iruka village, Niwa District, Owari Province. In the early {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|qid=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, for new field development under the {{ill|lt=Owari Domain|Q1062072|qid=Q1062072|1=Owari Domain}}, an irrigation reservoir ({{ill|lt=Iruka Pond|Q927013|qid=Q927013|1=Lake Iruka}}) was built, and Iruka village was submerged. The people of Iruka village relocated to surrounding areas, and Mushika Shrine was also relocated.

In {{ill|lt=1632|Q6865|qid=Q6865|1=1632}} ({{ill|lt=Kan'ei|Q1192913|qid=Q1192913|1=Kan'ei}} 9), construction of Iruka Pond began. The shrine was decided to move to Maehara Shinden, where the largest number of Iruka villagers relocated, and in {{ill|lt=1635|Q6879|qid=Q6879|1=1635}} (Kan'ei 12) it was transferred to the current site.

The current shrine building is said to date from that relocation.

In {{ill|lt=1868|Q7717|qid=Q7717|1=1868}} (Meiji 1), it became a {{ill|lt=Sonsha|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
*{{ill|UNKNOWN|qid=Q478504|lt=Kunitokotachi-no-Mikoto|1=Kuni-no-Tokotachi}}
